{
  "system_prompt": "You are a helpful assistant that provides detailed and accurate information based on the given text. Your responses should be structured, clear, and focused on the key points of the text. Avoid adding any external information or assumptions not supported by the text.",
  "response": {
    "summary": "This text discusses a comprehensive system for correcting customer locations in q-commerce (quick commerce), which involves identifying inaccurate addresses and correcting them using geocoders. The system includes a classifier to detect inaccurate addresses and a geocoder to correct them. The text evaluates several geocoding models (Seq2Seq, UAM, SAM) and compares their performance using metrics like delivery deviation (DD), relative delivery deviation (RDD), and relative delivery precision (RDP). The results show that while the SAM model performs best in terms of accuracy, the Seq2Seq model has lower DD and better scalability when deployed across different regions in India. The system is validated through real-world deployment, showing a reduction in delivery deviation after location correction.",
    "key_points": [
      "The system for correcting customer locations in q-commerce includes a classifier to identify inaccurate addresses and a geocoder to correct them.",
      "Several geocoding models (Seq2Seq, UAM, SAM) are evaluated for their performance in correcting inaccurate addresses.",
      "Metrics such as delivery deviation (DD), relative delivery deviation (RDD), and relative delivery precision (RDP) are used to assess the models' effectiveness.",
      "The Seq2Seq model, while correcting addresses over larger distances, has lower DD and better scalability when deployed across different regions in India.",
      "The system is validated through real-world deployment, showing a reduction in delivery deviation after location correction.",
      "The Union model, which combines usable predictions from the Seq2Seq, UAM, and SAM models, achieves a significant improvement in order coverage over the DBSCAN model."
    ],
    "evaluation": {
      "models": {
        "Seq2Seq": {
          "strengths": [
            "Lower mean and median DD",
            "Better scalability across regions in India"
          ],
          "weaknesses": [
            "Lower order coverage compared to UAM and SAM"
          ]
        },
        "UAM": {
          "strengths": [
            "Good order coverage",
            "Correction limited to H8 cell of captured location"
          ],
          "weaknesses": [
            "Higher DD compared to Seq2Seq"
          ]
        },
        "SAM": {
          "strengths": [
            "Best-performing model in terms of accuracy",
            "Significantly higher order coverage"
          ],
          "weaknesses": [
            "Higher DD compared to Seq2Seq"
          ]
        }
      },
      "metrics": {
        "DD": "Measures the Haversine distance between the predicted location and the delivery location. Lower DD indicates better accuracy.",
        "RDD": "Measures the relative closeness of the predicted location to the delivery location compared to the captured location. Higher RDD indicates better correction.",
        "RDP": "Measures the fraction of addresses for which the predicted location is more accurate than the captured location. Higher RDP indicates better correction."
      },
      "deployment": {
        "location": "The system is deployed across 3 large Indian cities in South India, with the Seq2Seq model scaled pan-India using four regional models.",
        "results": "The DD decreased by an average of 143 meters after location correction, validating the scalability of the approach."
      }
    },
    "conclusion": "The system for correcting customer locations in q-commerce is effective and scalable, with the Seq2Seq model showing strong performance in reducing delivery deviation. The Union model, combining predictions from multiple models, achieves a significant improvement in order coverage while maintaining high accuracy."
  }
