{
  "llm_response": "The LLM has successfully resolved the user's request to change the merchant classification from 'Four Points by Sheraton' to 'Four Points Service Station' based on the provided context, including the MCC code, receipt information, and memos. The LLM used these signals to determine that the request was legitimate and aligned with the user's intent. The action taken was to reassign the transaction to the more fitting merchant, which was confirmed by the LLM's rationale. The user will see the updated merchant name on the front end in seconds. If the LLM had rejected the request, a second LLM would have rewritten the rejection reason in plain language for the user. The evaluation of the agent's performance has shown that fewer than 10% of transactions receive a second correction request, and only 1 out of 4 requests are rejected, indicating strong performance and user satisfaction.",
  "evaluation_metrics": {
    "rejection_rate": "1 out of 4 requests",
    "second_correction_requests": "Fewer than 10% of transactions",
    "evaluation_strategies": [
      {
        "name": "Manual Evaluation",
        "strength": "Very Strong",
        "scalability": "Not Scalable",
        "impact_on_development": "Rapid Iteration"
      },
      {
        "name": "Count Repeated Requests",
        "strength": "Strong",
        "scalability": "Scales",
        "impact_on_development": "Easy to Set Up"
      },
      {
        "name": "Count Rejections",
        "strength": "Strong",
        "scalability": "Scales",
        "impact_on_development": "Easy to Set Up"
      },
      {
        "name": "LLM Judge",
        "strength": "Very Strong",
        "scalability": "Scales",
        "impact_on_development": "Requires Cycles"
      }
    ]
  },
  "guardrails": {
    "post_processing": "Enabled to catch LLM hallucinations",
    "action_limitations": "LLM is restricted to low-impact actions unless explicitly allowed for high-impact changes",
    "rejection_reasoning": "LLM rejection reasons are rewritten in plain language by a second LLM for user clarity"
  },
  "approach_summary": "The LLM was provided with context from transaction card acceptor names, MCC codes, receipt information, and user memos to determine the legitimacy of the request. A RAG approach was used to fetch related merchants, and guardrails were implemented to ensure the LLM only took appropriate actions. The evaluation strategies included manual review, counting repeated requests, counting rejections, and using an LLM judge to assess the agent's performance. The results indicate strong performance with low rejection and correction rates."
