{
  "ai_response": "The article describes the development of a machine learning model for shape recognition in Canva's Draw feature. The model uses client-side processing with a Recurrent Neural Network (RNN) and a Long Short Term Memory (LSTM) layer to analyze user-drawn shapes. The model is optimized for performance and size, with a total of approximately 64,109 parameters and a size of around 250 kilobytes. The model is deployed in the client application, allowing the feature to work offline and with low latency. The model uses a template-matching approach to align user-drawn paths with vector-graphic representations of predefined shapes. The development process involved data collection, hyperparameter tuning, and addressing challenges related to varying drawing speeds and model confidence. The feature is part of Canva's efforts to enhance user creativity and collaboration through machine learning.",
  "ai_response_type": "text"
}

